# Technology Stack Guide

## Project Overview

Aegis is an autonomous AI surgical monitoring and clinical workflow agent. This guide outlines the technology stack and development standards.

## Development Standards

### Code Quality
- Write clean, maintainable, and well-documented code
- Follow language-specific style guides and best practices
- Include type hints/annotations where applicable
- Write unit tests for critical functionality
- Use meaningful variable and function names

### Healthcare Data Handling
- Always follow HIPAA compliance requirements
- Encrypt sensitive data in transit and at rest
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Log access to PHI (Protected Health Information) appropriately
- Never commit sensitive data or credentials to version control

### API Design
- Use RESTful principles for API endpoints
- Follow FHIR REST API conventions for healthcare data
- Implement proper error handling and status codes
- Include API versioning in endpoints
- Document APIs with OpenAPI/Swagger specifications

### Real-time Monitoring
- Use appropriate protocols for real-time data streaming (WebSockets, MQTT, etc.)
- Implement proper buffering and error recovery for monitoring data
- Handle connection failures gracefully
- Ensure low-latency processing for critical monitoring alerts

### Testing
- Write tests for all critical paths
- Include integration tests for FHIR API interactions
- Test error scenarios and edge cases
- Maintain good test coverage for core functionality

## Architecture Principles

- **Modularity**: Design components to be loosely coupled and highly cohesive
- **Scalability**: Consider horizontal scaling for monitoring and processing workloads
- **Reliability**: Implement proper error handling, retries, and fallback mechanisms
- **Security**: Follow defense-in-depth security principles
- **Observability**: Include logging, metrics, and tracing for system monitoring
